'''Kobbie Boateng Mainoo''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|ɒ|b|i|_|ˈ|m|eɪ|n|uː}};<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 November 2024 |title=10 Things Man United's Kobbie Mainoo Can't Live Without {{!}} 10 Essentials |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fklEEx_6G80&t=4s |access-date=26 April 2025 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[GQ]]}}</ref> born 19 April 2005) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|ManchesU}} club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]]. He is known for his dribbling and composure.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" />

Mainoo is a graduate of [[Manchester United F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Manchester United's youth system]] and won the [[Jimmy Murphy Young Player of the Year]] award in 2023. He made his first-team debut in an [[EFL Cup]] match in January 2023. Mainoo played for England from [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]] youth level, before making his debut for the senior team in March 2024, and earning more than ten caps since then. He was included in the England squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] and the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

==Early life==
Kobbie Boateng Mainoo<ref>{{cite web|title=2022/23 Premier League squads confirmed|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/2786707|publisher=Premier League|date=16 September 2022|access-date=26 December 2022}}</ref> was born on 19 April 2005<ref name="PremProfile">{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/players/516895/kobbie-mainoo/overview |title=Kobbie Mainoo: Overview |publisher=Premier League |access-date=7 March 2026}}</ref> in [[Stockport]], Greater Manchester in England,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/mar/07/kobbie-mainoo-plans-to-reject-manchester-united-contract-and-move-abroad |title=Kobbie Mainoo plans to reject Manchester United contract and move abroad |first=Will |last=Unwin |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 March 2025 |access-date=7 March 2026}}</ref> to parents from [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Blanche|first=Phil|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/kobbie-mainoo-ghana-stockport-erik-ten-hag-fa-youth-cup-b2515120.html|title=Stockport star shining for Man Utd – England's latest call-up Kobbie Mainoo|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=19 March 2024|access-date=23 March 2024}}</ref> His older brother is Jordan Mainoo-Hames, who appeared as a contestant on the [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 5)|fifth series]] of ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kenmare|first=Jack|title=Fans are only just discovering who Kobbie Mainoo's older brother is|url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/football-news/man-utd/kobbie-mainoo-man-utd-premier-league-love-island-871387-20231209|website=SPORTBible|date=9 December 2023|access-date=19 December 2023}}</ref> He was raised in [[Cheadle Hulme]], a suburb of Stockport.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitwell|first=Laurie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5308162/2024/03/01/kobbie-mainoo-manchester-united-background/|title=The making of Kobbie Mainoo: 'United and City were chasing him when he was six'|website=The Athletic|date=1 March 2024|access-date=23 March 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Mainoo started his youth career at Cheadle & Gatley Junior Football Club.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|last=Fay|first=Richard|title=Manchester United might be about to unleash their own future midfield star vs Cadiz|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-united-kobbie-mainoo-news-25684009|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=7 December 2022|access-date=10 January 2023}}</ref> He then joined Failsworth Dynamos, where he played as a forward.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/story-telling/12028/13148353/next-up-how-kobbie-mainoo-became-manchester-uniteds-main-man |title=How Kobbie Mainoo became England's man for the big occasion |website=skysports.com |access-date=6 April 2025}}</ref> He was scouted for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at the age of six,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bartram|first=Steve|title=Must read: The rise and rise of Kobbie Mainoo |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/kobbie-mainoo-ascent-from-the-man-utd-academy|date=27 March 2024|access-date=12 July 2024|website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> signed up at the age of seven,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whitwell|first=Laurie|title=The making of Kobbie Mainoo, United's 'special' teenage talent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5308162/2024/03/01/kobbie-mainoo-manchester-united-background/|work=[[The Athletic]]|issn=0362-4331|date=1 March 2024|access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref> and joined the academy at the age of nine. Mainoo studied at [[Ashton-on-Mersey School]].<ref name=":0" />

===Manchester United===
====2022–2023====
Mainoo signed his first professional contract with Manchester United in May 2022.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fay|first=Richard|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kobbie-mainoo-manchester-united-contract-23977503|title=Manchester United starlet Kobbie Mainoo signs first professional deal|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=17 May 2022|access-date=16 October 2022}}</ref> His performances earned him a call-up to the first-team squad for training in October.<ref name="UnitedProfile">{{cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/players-and-staff/detail/kobbie-mainoo|title=Kobbie Mainoo {{!}} Player profile {{!}} Man Utd|website=Manchester United F.C.|access-date=14 July 2024}}</ref>

Mainoo was named on the bench for the first time on 16 October 2022, for a [[2022–23 Premier League|Premier League]] match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Railston|first=Steven|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-united-kobbie-mainoo-newcastle-25275884|title=Who is Kobbie Mainoo? Meet the Manchester United youngster named on the bench vs Newcastle |newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=16 October 2022|access-date=16 October 2022}}</ref> followed by making his senior debut on 10 January 2023, starting in a 3–0 home win over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in the quarter-final of the [[2022–23 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Stone|first=Simon|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64149053|title=Manchester United 3–0 Charlton Athletic|website=BBC Sport|date=10 January 2023|access-date=10 January 2023}}</ref> He continued to be part of the squad in both the semi-final legs and secured his first senior trophy, as United went along to win the final against Newcastle 
United.<ref name="Carabao2023" /> He made his league debut on 19 February by coming on as a substitute in a 3–0 home win against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kerr|first=Joshua|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-and-video-highlights-man-utd-v-leicester-city-premier-league-19-february-2023|title=Manchester United 3 Leicester City 0|website=Manchester United F.C.|date=19 February 2023|access-date=20 February 2023}}</ref>

====2023–2024====
Mainoo travelled with the Manchester United squad on their [[2023–24 Manchester United F.C. season#Pre-season and friendlies|2023–24 pre-season tour]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=Luckhurst|first=Samuel|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/man-united-tour-squad-news-27355310|title=Manchester United confirm pre-season tour squad|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=19 July 2023|access-date=19 July 2023}}</ref> However, he picked up an injury which kept him out for the start of the upcoming season.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mamaniyat|first=Abdullah|url=https://reddevilarmada.com/2023/08/18/erik-ten-hag-provides-kobbie-mainoo-injury-timescale/|title=Erik Ten Hag provides Kobbie Mainoo injury timescale|website=Red Devil Armada|date=18 August 2023|access-date=20 September 2023|archive-date=29 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929012323/https://reddevilarmada.com/2023/08/18/erik-ten-hag-provides-kobbie-mainoo-injury-timescale/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Returning from injury, Mainoo made his first league start for Manchester United on 26 November 2023, in a 3–0 [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League]] victory away to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], in which he was named [[Player of the match#Association football|man of the match]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13017129/kobbie-mainoo-man-utd-youngsters-full-premier-league-debut-against-everton-praised-by-gary-neville-and-roy-keane|title=Kobbie Mainoo: Man Utd youngster's full Premier League debut against Everton praised by Gary Neville and Roy Keane|website=Sky Sports|date=27 November 2023|access-date=27 November 2023}}</ref> On 29 November, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut, coming off the bench in a [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] 3–3 away draw against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Glendenning|first=Barry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2023/nov/29/galatasaray-v-manchester-united-champions-league-live|title=Galatasaray 3–3 Manchester United: Champions League – as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=29 November 2023|access-date=29 November 2023}}</ref>

On 28 January 2024, Mainoo scored his first goal for Manchester United in a 4–2 win away to [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] in the [[2023–24 FA Cup|FA Cup]] fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68110828|title=FA Cup: Newport County 2–4 Manchester United avoid upset at Rodney Parade|website=BBC Sport|date=28 January 2024|access-date=28 January 2024}}</ref> A few days later, on 1 February, he scored his first Premier League goal, a stoppage time winner in a 4–3 away victory over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Emma|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68090233|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 3–4 Manchester United: Kobbie Mainoo scores 97th-minute winner in thriller|website=BBC Sport|date=1 February 2024|access-date=1 February 2024}}</ref> The goal was later awarded [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] for February 2024.<ref name="GOTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3922061|title=Mainoo's late stunner wins Budweiser Goal of the Month award|publisher=Premier League|date=8 March 2024|access-date=8 March 2024}}</ref> On 7 April, he netted his first professional goal at [[Old Trafford]] in a 2–2 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.–Manchester United F.C. rivalry|rivals]] [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68702106|title=Manchester United 2–2 Liverpool: Mohamed Salah scores late penalty to snatch point for Reds|website=BBC Sport|date=8 April 2024|access-date=8 April 2024}}</ref>

In the [[2024 FA Cup final|FA Cup final]], Mainoo scored the eventual winning goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Manchester derby|local rivals]] [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and was awarded Man of the Match.<ref name="SkySports">{{cite news|last=Yew|first=Oliver|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/man-city-vs-man-utd/report/504674|title=Man City 1–2 Man Utd: Erik ten Hag's side end season on high with stunning FA Cup final win at Wembley|date=26 May 2024|access-date=26 May 2024|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> He became the first English teenager to score in a final since [[Steve MacKenzie]] in [[1981 FA Cup final|1981]] and the youngest since [[John Sissons (footballer)|John Sissons]] in [[1964 FA Cup final|1964]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://theanalyst.com/eu/2024/05/manchester-city-vs-manchester-united-stats-fa-cup-final/|title=Manchester City 1–2 Manchester United Stats: Teenage Dreams for United As They Win FA Cup Final|date=25 May 2024|access-date=26 May 2024|author=Opta Analyst|website=theanalyst.com}}</ref> His performances for the season were widely praised, with him being nominated for the [[Premier League Young Player of the Season]] award.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Carney|first=Sam|title=Mainoo nominated for Young Player of the Season|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/kobbie-mainoo-nominated-for-premier-league-young-player-of-the-season|date=May 9, 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref>

====2024–present====
On 17 October 2024, Manchester United confirmed that Mainoo would be out for a few weeks following a muscle injury he picked up during a 0–0 away to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 6 October.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Manchester United's Mainoo out for a few weeks due to muscle injury |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/manchester-uniteds-mainoo-out-few-weeks-due-muscle-injury-2024-10-18/ |date=18 October 2024|access-date=1 February 2025|website=Reuters}}</ref> He made his return on 1 December 2024, starting in a 4–0 win against Everton in new head coach [[Ruben Amorim]]'s first Premier League match at Old Trafford.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hafez|first=Shampon|title=Manchester United 4–0 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ckglqgrwgx0t |date=1 December 2024|access-date=1 February 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 30 January 2025, Mainoo scored his first goal of the season and his first in Europe in a 2–0 away win over [[FCSB]]. He also got an assist and was named [[Player of the match|man of the match]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Rindl|first=Joe|title=FCSB 0–2 Manchester United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ce3n55vyyvkt |date=30 January 2025|access-date=1 February 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 17 April 2025, following a return from injury, Mainoo scored a last-minute extra-time equaliser in the second-leg of a [[2024-25 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] tie against [[Olympique Lyon]]. United scored only a minute later with a header from [[Harry Maguire]] to win 5–4, as they became the first team to score two goals in the 120th minute of a European match.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hall |first=Peter |title=Maguire's 121st minute winner sends Man Utd through to Europa League semis |date=18 April 2025 |access-date=18 April 2025 |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/maguires-121st-minute-winner-sends-man-utd-through-europa-league-semis-2025-04-17 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> On 30 April 2026, he extended his contract with the club until 2031.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/kobbie-mainoo-signs-new-man-utd-contract-until-june-2031 |title=Mainoo signs new contract |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=30 April 2026 }}</ref> A few days later, on 3 May, he netted the winner in a 3–2 victory over Liverpool, securing his club's place in the [[2026–27 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], and completing first league double over their rivals since the 2015–16 season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stone |first=Simon |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cwy2421dj2vt |title=Manchester United 3–2 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
Mainoo has represented England at [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], and [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] youth levels, and at the [[England national football team|senior level]].<ref name="wfnat"/>

In March 2024, Mainoo was called up to the senior squad for the first time for England's [[Friendly (association football)|friendlies]] against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], after previously being drafted for the under-21s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/13098125/kobbie-mainoo-man-utd-midfielder-handed-first-england-call-up-after-being-drafted-in-from-under-21s|title=Kobbie Mainoo: Man Utd midfielder handed first England call-up after being drafted in from Under-21s|website=Sky Sports|date=19 March 2024|access-date=19 March 2024}}</ref> Aged 18, he made his debut on 23 March as a substitute for [[Conor Gallagher]] in a 1–0 defeat to Brazil at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68647860|title=England 0–1 Brazil: Teenager Endrick scores late winner at Wembley|website=BBC Sport|date=23 March 2024|access-date=23 March 2024}}</ref> He made his first England start in a 2–2 draw against Belgium, in which he was named man of the match.<ref>{{cite web|last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68603249|title=England 2–2 Belgium: Late Jude Bellingham goal saves hosts from second successive Wembley defeat|website=BBC Sport|date=26 March 2024|access-date=26 March 2024}}</ref>

On 6 June, Mainoo was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno|title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024|website=BBC Sport|date=6 June 2024|access-date=6 June 2024}}</ref> He made his competitive debut in the team's opening match, playing the last four minutes as a substitute for [[Jude Bellingham]] in a 1–0 win over [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Serbia 0–1 England LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cz992dxd4xwt#Line-ups|website=BBC Sport|access-date=17 June 2024}}</ref> On 25 June, he played the second half against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] in a 0–0 draw in the team's final [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group C#England vs Slovenia|group stage match]], replacing Conor Gallagher at half time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036189--england-vs-slovenia/lineups/|title=England vs Slovenia {{!}} Line-ups|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=25 June 2024}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#England vs Slovakia|round of 16 match]] against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], he became the third-youngest player to start for England at a knockout stage of a major tournament in a 2–1 win.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bostock|first=Adam|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/kobbie-mainoo-makes-first-tournament-start-as-england-beat-slovakia-in-euro-2024-last-16|title=Kobbie Mainoo makes first tournament start as England beat Slovakia in Euro 2024 last-16 tie|date=30 June 2024|access-date=1 July 2024|website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> On 10 July, in a 2–1 win in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#Netherlands vs England|semi-finals]] against [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], he became the youngest England player to play a semi-final of a major tournament.<ref>{{cite news|last=Segar|first=David|url=https://theanalyst.com/eu/2024/07/netherlands-vs-england-stats-euro-2024-live/|title=Netherlands 1–2 England Stats: Super Sub Watkins Fires Three Lions Into Euro 2024 Final|date=11 July 2024|access-date=14 July 2024|website=theanalyst.com}}</ref> Four days later, he started in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 final|final]], which ended in a 2–1 defeat to [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref name="Euro2024final">{{cite news|last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cp68zzx8x4rt|title=Spain 2–1 England: Heartbreak for England in Euro 2024 Final|website=BBC Sport|date=14 July 2024|access-date=15 July 2024|archive-date=15 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715010859/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cp68zzx8x4rt|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 21 May 2026, Mainoo was named in England's 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup 2026]].  <ref>{{Cite web |last=Mokbel |first=Sami |date=2026-05-21 |title=England World Cup squad: Phil Foden, Cole Palmer and Trent Alexander-Arnold left out |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c78ke277pmdo |access-date=2026-05-27 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Mainoo is primarily a [[central midfielder]] who is also capable of playing as a [[defensive midfielder]] and [[attacking midfielder]].<ref name="position">{{cite news|last=Unwin|first=Will|title=Local hero: Kobbie Mainoo bringing cheer at troubled Manchester United|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/dec/01/local-hero-kobbie-mainoo-bringing-cheer-at-troubled-manchester-united|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=1 December 2023|access-date=2 February 2024}}</ref> An intelligent and composed player, he excels in driving the ball forward, using his [[Dribbling (association football)|dribbling]] skills to navigate through tight spaces and evade defenders.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|last=Clarke|first=Adrian|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3905433|title=How Mainoo has brought control to Man Utd's midfield|publisher=Premier League|date=22 February 2024|access-date=29 May 2024}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|last=Bate|first=Adam|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/13082805/kobbie-mainoo-s-manchester-united-magic-explained-how-does-the-teenager-find-time-and-space-that-others-cannot|title=Kobbie Mainoo's Manchester United magic explained: How does the teenager find time and space that others cannot?|website=Sky Sports|date=19 March 2024|access-date=29 May 2024}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web|last=Manship|first=Jack|url=https://totalfootballanalysis.com/teams/england/england-2024-overlooked-data-analysis-statistics|title=England 2024: Overlooked players – data analysis|website=totalfootballanalysis.com|date=19 March 2024|access-date=29 May 2024}}</ref> Former Manchester United defender [[Rio Ferdinand]] has compared his style of play to that of [[Clarence Seedorf]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Emma|last2=Stone|first2=Simon|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68176430|title=Wolves 3–4 Man Utd: Kobbie Mainoo continues rise to stardom with 'dream' winning goal|website=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2024|access-date=2 February 2024}}</ref> Former Manchester United manager [[Erik ten Hag]] praised his ability to "quickly adapt to high levels", as well as his willingness to progress and develop as a player.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peach|first=Simon|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/erik-ten-hag-kobbie-mainoo-manchester-united-england-lisandro-martinez-b2520625.html|title=Erik ten Hag expects Kobbie Mainoo to handle the hype after star England debut|work=The Independent|date=29 March 2024|access-date=30 March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hemingway|first=Rob|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/premier-league/2023-2024/erik-ten-hag-exclusive-manchester-united-boss-opens-up-on-kobbie-mainoo-and-alejandro-garnacho-incre_sto10001992/story.shtml|title=Erik ten Hag exclusive: Manchester United boss opens up on Kobbie Mainoo and Alejandro Garnacho 'incredible progress'|publisher=Eurosport|date=2 February 2024|access-date=2 February 2024}}</ref> Pundit and former United midfielder [[Paul Scholes]] praised him, saying that "[I] just love the way he receives the ball, the calmness, the awareness of what's around him, and of course big goals in big games."<ref name="SkySports"/>

